The relative and absolute configuration of 1 was established based on the NOESY ( Fig. 3 ) and single crystal X-ray diffraction. The NOESY correlations of NH/H-1 and H-1/H-7 indicated that these protons were on the same face of the decalin ring and arbitrarily assigned β -orientations. The α -orientations of H-5 and H-6 was determined by the NOESY correlations of H 3 -20/H-6 and H-6/H-5. In addition, the carbon resonances at δ C 41.6 (C-1), 36.6 (C-6), 36.7 (C-9), and 18.9 (C-20) in 1 further confirmed the trans fusion of the decalin ring (
;
;
). Inspection of the literature data on kalihinols with a Cl-bearing pyran ring indicated that the values of carbon resonance for C-12 is characteristic for determination of the stereochemistry of Cl-14, namely owing to γ- gauche effect, ~28–33 and ~37–40 for axial -Cl and equatorial -Cl, respectively (
;
;
;
). The chlorine atom in 1 was determined to be equatorial by the carbon chemical shifts at δ C 38.3 (C-12). Finally, the absolute configuration of 1 was unambiguously determined as 1 S , 4 R , 5 R , 6 S , 7 S , 10 S , 11 R , and 14 S by single crystal X-ray diffraction using Cu K α radiation ( Fig. 4 ).

Analysis of the 1D and 2D NMR data revealed that 2 possessed the same carbon skeleton as 1 ( Tables 1 and 3 ). A significant difference between 1 and 2 was found in the chemical shift of C-12 ( δ C 29.1 in 2 instead of δ C 38.3 in 1 ), which was caused by the γ- gauche effect, indicating an axial orientation of Cl-14 (
;
;
;
). The chemical shifts of C-1 to C-10 and NOESY correlations of NH/H-1, H-1/H-7, H 3 -20/H-6, and H-6/H-5 indicated the relative configuration of the decalin ring in 2 was the same as 1 . The relative configurations of C-7 and C- 11 in 2 were determined as S * and R *, respectively, from NOESY correlations of H 3 -18/H-6, H 3 -18/H-8b, and H-8a/H-12, as shown in the Newman projection ( Fig. 3 ).

