The 1 H and 13 C NMR data of compounds 5 and 6 were similar to compounds 3 and 4 ( Tables 1–3 ), respectively, suggested they were structural analogs, in which an iso-amyl ester group in 3 and 4 was replaced by a phenethyl ester group in 5 and 6 . The phenethyl ester group was determined by a COSY correlation of H-8’/H-9’/H-10 ′ and HMBC correlations of H 2 -6’/C-5 ′ , C-7 ′ , and C-8 ′ , H-9’/C-7 ′ and H-10’/C- 8’ ( Fig. 2 ). The relative configurations of 5 and 6 were established by observation of NOESY correlations of NH/H-1, H-1/H-7, H 3 -20/H-6, H- 6/H-5, H 3 -18/H-6, H 3 -18/H-8b, and H-8a/H-12 ( Fig. 3 ) and the carbon chemical shifts at δ C 38.3 (C-12) in 5 and 29.1 (C-12) in 6 which were found to be the same with 3 and 4 (
